ility and invisibility emerged over the past forty years—bookended by the right-wing presidencies of Ronald Reagan and Donald Trump—and how Central American immigrants and subsequent generations have contested their rhetorical disfiguration. Drawing from popular films and TV, news reporting, and social media, Padilla shows how Central Americans in the United States have been constituted as belonging nowhere, imagined as permanent refugees outside the boundaries of even minority representation. Yet in documentaries about cross-border transit through Mexico, street murals, and other media, US Central Americans have counteracted their exclusion in ways that defy dominant paradigms of citizenship and integration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCentral American Americans. 0aCentral Americans in motion pictures. 0aCentral AmericansxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aCentral AmericansxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aCentral AmericansxPress coveragezUnited States. 0aCentral AmericanszUnited States. 0aImmigrants in mass media. 0aMass media and immigrantszUnited States. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in mass media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCentral Americans, Guatemalans, citizenship, Salvadorans, immigrant.  aimmigrants, Hondurans, refugee, refugees.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas P